                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d111">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A5/466: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chargé in France</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Marriner</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-08-29T14:00:00-04:00"
                            >August 29, 1935—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>352. In discussing the subject of our 348 with particular reference to third
                    paragraph mentioning French view that “if quantitative limitation proved
                    impossible, there should at least be sought an agreement as to qualitative
                    limits”, you should not give the impression that we are seeking or would agree
                    to a qualitative limitation only, but should rather stress the note that we do
                    not wish to discuss any particular or individual changes from the principles of
                    the existing treaties separately from the comprehensive consideration of all the
                    elements of the problem.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
